SOLID Principles

S - single responsibility Principle
O - Open / Closed Principle
L - Liskov substitution principle
I - interface segmentation principle
D - Dependency Inversion Principle

Advantages of using solid design principles
- helps to write better code
- avoid duplicate code
- easy to maintain
- easy to understand
- flexible software
- reduce complexity

SRP
    A class should have only one reason to change
    meaning it should have one and only job or responsibility

OCP
    A class should be open for extension but closed for modification
    means that the new functionality can be added through the inheritance rather than by modifying existing code
    As existing code is already tested and deployed in production,  adding modifications would introduce an additional risk and require addintional testing effort

LSP
    objects of a superclass should be replaceable with objects of its subclasses without breaking the applicatoin
    means if class B is a subtype of class A, then we should be able to replace objects of A with B without breaking the behaviour of the program

    or

    any implementation of the interface should be substitutable for another without breaking expected behaviour or contracts

    subclass should be able to extend the  capability of the parent class should not narrow it down.


ISP
    Interface should be such that the client should not implement unnecessary functons they do not need.
    classes should not be forced to implement methods that don't support
    code becomes bloated with empty or error-throwing methods
    violates the principle that clients shouldnt depend on  unused interfaces

DIP
    high level compoents should not depend on low level components directly; instead they should depend on abstractions


